On Tue, Jan 3, 2012 at 1:44 PM, Jan Algermissen
&lt;jan.algermissen@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; On Jan 3, 2012, at 2:01 PM, Mike Kelly wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; The is no shared understanding that the server needs to know about.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Of course there is - a server has to establish a specific
&gt;&gt; understanding of an incoming POST body to a resource in order to
&gt;&gt; process it in a specific way.
&gt;
&gt; When was the last time you implemented a POST handler of a resource and thought in any way about what the client expects?
&gt;
&gt; Answer: &quot;never&quot;; because it is completely up to the resource what to do upon POST.

- What the resource does upon POST is determined by understanding the
semantics of the application it is part of (e.g. processing
form-encoded credit card details).

- What the client POSTs is determined by its understanding of the
semantics of the application it is navigating through (e.g. submitting
form-encoded credit card details via a payment form).

This is a shared understanding, controlled by hypermedia, from two
different perspectives - server vs client.
